Parameter and Summary Values

require(knitr)
## Loading required package: knitr
DF2<-data.frame(t(apply(AssignmentData[,1:7],2,function(x=AssignmentData)lm(AssignmentData[,8]~x)$coeff)),t(t(apply(AssignmentData[,1:7],2,function(x=AssignmentData)summary(lm(AssignmentData[,8]~x))$r.squared))),t(t(apply(AssignmentData[,1:7],2,function(x=AssignmentData)summary(lm(AssignmentData[,8]~x))$sigma^2))),t(t(apply(AssignmentData[,1:7],2,function(x=AssignmentData)summary(lm(AssignmentData[,8]~x))$coefficients[1,4]))),t(t(apply(AssignmentData[,1:7],2,function(x=AssignmentData)summary(lm(AssignmentData[,8]~x))$coefficients[2,4]))))
names(DF2)<-c("Intercept","Slope","R-Squared","Unexplained Variance","Intercept P-Value","Slope P-Value")
kable(DF2)
## 
## 
## |         | Intercept| Slope| R-Squared| Unexplained Variance| Intercept P-Value| Slope P-Value|
## |:--------|---------:|-----:|---------:|--------------------:|-----------------:|-------------:|
## |USGG3M   |    -11.72| 2.508|    0.9628|               2.8571|                 0|             0|
## |USGG6M   |    -12.10| 2.497|    0.9744|               1.9673|                 0|             0|
## |USGG2YR  |    -13.06| 2.400|    0.9966|               0.2588|                 0|             0|
## |USGG3YR  |    -13.86| 2.456|    0.9979|               0.1597|                 0|             0|
## |USGG5YR  |    -15.44| 2.569|    0.9917|               0.6383|                 0|             0|
## |USGG10YR |    -18.06| 2.787|    0.9692|               2.3668|                 0|             0|
## |USGG30YR |    -21.09| 3.070|    0.9353|               4.9673|                 0|             0|

From the table, we see that USGG2YR and USGG3YR have the largest R-Squared values (and therefore the largest correlation). Furthermore, the inputs that have the lowest Unexplained Variance are also USGG2YR and USGG3YR. Due to this, these two inputs most likely best explain the output. It is also of note that these two have the smallest slopes. Lastly, all p-values are so small to the point that they are rounded down to zero, which indicates that all are significant.

These four models all include differing subsets of predictors. From their linear model summaries, we can see that all of them have rather high Adjusted R-Squared values (greater than 0.9). Also, from the anova summaries that compare them to the full model, we observe that all of the p-values are significant. This means that the full models, using all seven predictors, do indeed add something to the model. So far, it is looking like the full model may be the best.

We would ideally like to test all combinations of predictors. However, that is not very feasible and would take up a large amount of time and space. So, we can use other tools to attempt to test these subsets of predictors without needing to do so manually. The function stepAIC from the MASS package, can test each model, starting with the full model and removing the predictors one by one in a stepwise fashion in order to test if it had an impact.

## stepAIC method
require(MASS)
## Loading required package: MASS
stepAIC(RegModelCompare.full,direction="backward")
## Start:  AIC=-336591
## AssignmentDataRegCompare[, 8] ~ AssignmentDataRegCompare[, 1] + 
##     AssignmentDataRegCompare[, 2] + AssignmentDataRegCompare[,

As we see from the output of stepAIC, the model including all seven predictors is preferred. The message that is outputted along with the results furthermore tells us that the model with all seven predictors has an essentially perfect fit, making further tinkering fairly useless.

If we are still not satisfied with this, however, we can also use the regsubsets function from the leaps package, which gives us a graphical output to aid in our selection.

require(leaps)
## Loading required package: leaps
AssignmentDataRC<-read.csv("RegressionAssignmentData2014.csv",row.names=1,header=T,sep=",")
leaps<-regsubsets(AssignmentDataRC[,8]~AssignmentDataRC[,1]+AssignmentDataRC[,2]+AssignmentDataRC[,3]+AssignmentDataRC[,4]+AssignmentDataRC[,5]+AssignmentDataRC[,6]+AssignmentDataRC[,7],data=AssignmentDataRC,nbest=4)
plot(leaps,scale="adjr2")

From the plot, we can see that there are many subsets of predictors that have a high Adjusted R-Squared value associated with them. However, up at the top, indicating the largest Adjust R-Squared value, is the model with all seven predictors. Therefore, from reasons here and above, we will ultimately select the model that includes all seven inputs as predictors.

One note to be made, before moving on, is that if there were any additional factors affecting our model selection (e.g., cost of getting or processing data), it may change our decision. Since there are so many subsets of predictors that give us a decent model with a high Adjusted R-Squared, an argument could be made to omit certain ones if it meant saving costs or increasing efficiency elsewhere. In this project, however, we do not have such constraints. Thus, we choose all seven predictors because it is the best model, regardless of it being marginally so.
